023/**
024 * A generic insertion-ordered hash map with with a fast implementation, originally from fastutil as
025 * Object2ObjectLinkedOpenHashMap but modified to support constant-time indexed access of keys, values, and entries,
026 * reordering, and optional hash strategies for unusual keys, such as arrays or usually-dense numeric values.
027 * <br>
028 * Instances of this class use a hash table to represent a map. The table is filled up to a specified <em>load factor</em>, and then doubled in size to accommodate new entries. If the table is
029 * emptied below <em>one fourth</em> of the load factor, it is halved in size. However, halving is not performed when deleting entries from an iterator, as it would interfere with the iteration
030 * process.
031 * <br>
032 * Note that {@link #clear()} does not modify the hash table size. Rather, a family of {@linkplain #trim() trimming methods} lets you control the size of the table; this is particularly useful if
033 * you reuse instances of this class.
034 * <br>
035 * Iterators generated by this map will enumerate pairs in the same order in which they have been added to the map (addition of pairs whose key is already present in the set does not change the
036 * iteration order). Note that this order has nothing in common with the natural order of the keys. The order is kept by means of a int-specialized list, {@link IntVLA}, and is modifiable with this
037 * class' {@link #reorder(int...)} and {@link #shuffle(IRNG)} methods, among other tools. It may be preferable to avoid instantiating an Iterator object and instead
038 * use a normal int-based for loop with {@link #getAt(int)} called in each iteration. Though this doesn't allow easy deletion of items during iteration, it may be the
039 * fastest way to iterate through an OrderedMap.
040 * <br>
041 * This class implements the interface of a sorted map, so to allow easy access of the iteration order: for instance, you can get the first key in iteration order with {@code firstKey()} without
042 * having to create an iterator; however, this class partially violates the {@link SortedMap} contract because all submap methods throw an exception and {@link #comparator()} returns always
043 * <code>null</code>.
044 * <br>
045 * Additional methods, such as <code>getAndMoveToFirst()</code>, make it easy to use instances of this class as a cache (e.g., with LRU policy).
046 * <br>
047 * This class allows approximately constant-time lookup of keys or values by their index in the ordering, which can
048 * allow some novel usage of the data structure. {@link OrderedSet} can be used like a list of unique elements, keeping
049 * order like a list does but also allowing rapid checks for whether an item exists in the OrderedSet, and OrderedMap
050 * can be used like that but with values associated as well (where OrderedSet uses contains(), OrderedMap uses
051 * containsKey()). You can also set the key and value at a position with {@link #putAt(Object, Object, int)}, or alter
052 * the key while keeping its value and index the same with {@link #alter(Object, Object)}. Reordering works here too,
053 * both with completely random orders from {@link #shuffle(IRNG)} or with a previously-generated ordering from
054 * {@link #reorder(int...)} (you can produce such an ordering for a given size and reuse it across multiple Ordered data
055 * structures with {@link IRNG#randomOrdering(int)}). Note that putAt() and {@link #removeAt(int)} do not run in constant
056 * time, and depending on the point of insertion/removal, they are likely to run in linear time (but also note that most
057 * insertion-ordered Maps and Sets don't allow insertion or removal at anywhere but the beginning or end of the order).
058 * <br>
059 * You can pass a {@link CrossHash.IHasher} instance such as {@link CrossHash#generalHasher} as an extra parameter to
060 * most of this class' constructors, which allows the OrderedMap to use arrays (usually primitive arrays) as keys. If
061 * you expect only one type of array, you can use an instance like {@link CrossHash#intHasher} to hash int arrays, or
062 * the aforementioned generalHasher to hash most kinds of arrays (it can't handle most multi-dimensional arrays well).
063 * If you aren't using arrays as keys, you don't need to give an IHasher to the constructor and can ignore this feature
064 * most of the time. However, the default IHasher this uses if none is specified performs a small but significant
065 * "mixing" step to make the default generated hashCode() implementation many classes use into a higher-quality
066 * random-like value. This isn't always optimal; if you plan to insert 1000 sequential Integer keys with some small
067 * amount of random Integers after them, then the mixing actually increases the likelihood of a collision and takes time
068 * to calculate. You could use a very simple IHasher in that case, relying on the fact that only Integers will be added:
069 * <pre>
070 * new CrossHash.IHasher() {
071 *     public int hash(Object data) { return (int)data; }
072 *     public boolean areEqual(Object left, Object right) { return Objects.equals(left, right); }
073 * };
074 * </pre>
075 * This is just one example of a case where a custom IHasher can be useful for performance reasons; there are also cases
076 * where an IHasher is needed to enforce hashing by identity or by value, which affect program logic. Note that the
077 * given IHasher is likely to be sub-optimal for many situations with Integer keys, and you may want to try a few
078 * different approaches if you know OrderedMap is a bottleneck in your application. If the IHasher is a performance
079 * problem, it will be at its worst if the OrderedMap needs to resize, and thus rehash, many times; this won't happen if
080 * the capacity is set correctly when the OrderedMap is created (with the capacity equal to or greater than the maximum
081 * number of entries that will be added).
082 * <br>
083 * Thank you, Sebastiano Vigna, for making FastUtil available to the public with such high quality.
084 * <br>
085 * See https://github.com/vigna/fastutil for the original library.
086 * @author Sebastiano Vigna (responsible for all the hard parts)
087 * @author Tommy Ettinger (mostly responsible for squashing several layers of parent classes into one monster class)
088 */

172    /**
173     * Creates a new OrderedMap.
174     * <p>
175     * <p>The actual table size will be the least power of two greater than <code>expected</code>/<code>f</code>.
176     *
177     * @param expected the expected number of elements in the hash set.
178     * @param f        the load factor.
179     */
180
181    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
182    public OrderedMap(final int expected, final float f) {
183        if (f <= 0 || f > 1)
184            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Load factor must be greater than 0 and smaller than or equal to 1");
185        if (expected < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("The expected number of elements must be nonnegative");
186        this.f = f;
187        n = arraySize(expected, f);
188        mask = n - 1;
189        maxFill = maxFill(n, f);
190        key = (K[]) new Object[n + 1];
191        value = (V[]) new Object[n + 1];
192        //link = new long[n + 1];
193        order = new IntVLA(expected);
194        hasher = CrossHash.mildHasher;
195    }

234     * Creates a new OrderedMap using the elements of two parallel arrays.
235     *
236     * @param keyArray the array of keys of the new OrderedMap.
237     * @param valueArray the array of corresponding values in the new OrderedMap.

242        this(keyArray.length, f);
243        if (keyArray.length != valueArray.length)
244            throw new IllegalArgumentException("The key array and the value array have different lengths (" + keyArray.length + " and " + valueArray.length + ")");

246            put(keyArray[i], valueArray[i]);

259     * Creates a new OrderedMap using the elements of two parallel arrays.
260     *
261     * @param keyColl the collection of keys of the new OrderedMap.
262     * @param valueColl the collection of corresponding values in the new OrderedMap.
263     * @param f the load factor.
264     * @throws IllegalArgumentException if <code>k</code> and <code>v</code> have different lengths.
265     */
266    public OrderedMap(final Collection<K> keyColl, final Collection<V> valueColl, final float f) {
267        this(keyColl.size(), f);
268        if (keyColl.size() != valueColl.size())
269            throw new IllegalArgumentException("The key array and the value array have different lengths (" + keyColl.size() + " and " + valueColl.size() + ")");
270        Iterator<K> ki = keyColl.iterator();
271        Iterator<V> vi = valueColl.iterator();
272        while (ki.hasNext() && vi.hasNext())
273        {
274            put(ki.next(), vi.next());
275        }
276    }

380    private int realSize() {
381        return containsNullKey ? size - 1 : size;
382    }

384    public void ensureCapacity(final int capacity) {
385        final int needed = arraySize(capacity, f);
386        if (needed > n)
387            rehash(needed);
388    }
389    private void tryCapacity(final long capacity) {
390        final int needed = (int) Math.min(
391                1 << 30,
392                Math.max(2, HashCommon.nextPowerOfTwo((long) Math.ceil(capacity
393                        / f))));
394        if (needed > n)
395            rehash(needed);
396    }
397    protected V removeEntry(final int pos) {
398        final V oldValue = value[pos];
399        value[pos] = null;
400        size--;
401        fixOrder(pos);
402        shiftKeys(pos);
403        if (size < maxFill / 4 && n > DEFAULT_INITIAL_SIZE)
404            rehash(n / 2);
405        return oldValue;
406    }
407    protected V removeNullEntry() {
408        containsNullKey = false;
409        key[n] = null;
410        final V oldValue = value[n];
411        value[n] = null;
412        size--;
413        fixOrder(n);
414        if (size < maxFill / 4 && n > DEFAULT_INITIAL_SIZE)
415            rehash(n / 2);
416        return oldValue;
417    }

419    /**
420     * Puts the first key in keyArray with the first value in valueArray, then the second in each and so on.
421     * The entries are all appended to the end of the iteration order, unless a key was already present. Then,
422     * its value is changed at the existing position in the iteration order.
423     * If the lengths of the two arrays are not equal, this puts a number of entries equal to the lesser length.
424     * If either array is null, this returns without performing any changes.
425     * @param keyArray an array of K keys that should usually have the same length as valueArray
426     * @param valueArray an array of V values that should usually have the same length as keyArray
427     */
428    public void putAll(final K[] keyArray, final V[] valueArray)
429    {
430        if(keyArray == null || valueArray == null)
431            return;
432        for (int i = 0; i < keyArray.length && i < valueArray.length; i++)
433            put(keyArray[i], valueArray[i]);
434
435    }

437    /**
438     * Puts all key-value pairs in the Map m into this OrderedMap.
439     * The entries are all appended to the end of the iteration order, unless a key was already present. Then,
440     * its value is changed at the existing position in the iteration order. This can take any kind of Map,
441     * including unordered HashMap objects; if the Map does not have stable ordering, the order in which entries
442     * will be appended is not stable either. For this reason, OrderedMap, LinkedHashMap, and TreeMap (or other
443     * SortedMap implementations) will work best when order matters.
444     * @param m a Map that should have the same or compatible K key and V value types; OrderedMap and TreeMap work best
445     */
446    public void putAll(Map<? extends K, ? extends V> m) {
447        if (f <= .5)
448            ensureCapacity(m.size()); // The resulting map will be sized for
449            // m.size() elements
450        else
451            tryCapacity(size() + m.size()); // The resulting map will be
452        int n = m.size();
453        final Iterator<? extends Map.Entry<? extends K, ? extends V>> i = m
454                .entrySet().iterator();
455        if (m instanceof OrderedMap) {
456            Entry<? extends K, ? extends V> e;
457            while (n-- != 0) {
458                e = i.next();
459                put(e.getKey(), e.getValue());
460            }
461        } else {
462            Map.Entry<? extends K, ? extends V> e;
463            while (n-- != 0) {
464                e = i.next();
465                put(e.getKey(), e.getValue());
466            }
467        }
468    }
469    private int insert(final K k, final V v) {
470        int pos;
471        if (k == null) {
472            if (containsNullKey)
473                return n;
474            containsNullKey = true;
475            pos = n;
476        } else {
477            K curr;
478            final K[] key = this.key;
479            // The starting point.
480            if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) != null) {
481                if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k))
482                    return pos;
483                while ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) != null)
484                    if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k))
485                        return pos;
486            }
487        }
488        key[pos] = k;
489        value[pos] = v;
490        order.add(pos);
491        if (size++ >= maxFill)
492            rehash(arraySize(size + 1, f));
493        return -1;
494    }
495    private int insertAt(final K k, final V v, final int idx) {
496        int pos;
497        if (k == null) {
498            if (containsNullKey)
499            {
500                fixOrder(n);
501                order.insert(idx, n);
502                return n;
503            }
504            containsNullKey = true;
505            pos = n;
506        } else {
507            K curr;
508            final K[] key = this.key;
509            // The starting point.
510            if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) != null) {
511                if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k))
512                {
513                    fixOrder(pos);
514                    order.insert(idx, pos);
515                    return pos;
516                }
517                while ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) != null)
518                    if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k))
519                    {
520                        fixOrder(pos);
521                        order.insert(idx, pos);
522                        return pos;
523                    }
524            }
525        }
526        key[pos] = k;
527        value[pos] = v;
528        order.insert(idx, pos);
529        if (size++ >= maxFill)
530            rehash(arraySize(size + 1, f));
531        return -1;
532    }
533    public V put(final K k, final V v) {
534        final int pos = insert(k, v);
535        if (pos < 0)
536            return defRetValue;
537        final V oldValue = value[pos];
538        value[pos] = v;
539        return oldValue;
540    }
541    public V putAt(final K k, final V v, final int idx) {
542        final int pos = insertAt(k, v, idx);
543        if (pos < 0)
544            return defRetValue;
545        final V oldValue = value[pos];
546        value[pos] = v;
547        return oldValue;
548    }

550    /**
551     * Changes the value at a specified {@code idx} in the iteration order to {@code v}, without involving keys at all.
552     * If {@code idx} isn't currently a valid index in the iteration order, this returns {@link #defaultReturnValue()}.
553     * @param v the new V value to assign
554     * @param idx the index in the iteration order to set {@code v} at
555     * @return the previous value held at {@code idx} in the iteration order, which may be null if the value was null
556     */
557    public V setAt(final V v, final int idx) {
558        if(idx < 0 || idx >= size)
559            return defRetValue;
560        final int pos = order.get(idx);
561        final V oldValue = value[pos];
562        value[pos] = v;
563        return oldValue;
564    }

566    /**
567     * Shifts left entries with the specified hash code, starting at the
568     * specified position, and empties the resulting free entry.
569     *
570     * @param pos
571     *            a starting position.
572     */
573    protected final void shiftKeys(int pos) {
574        // Shift entries with the same hash.
575        int last, slot;
576        K curr;
577        final K[] key = this.key;
578        for (;;) {
579            pos = ((last = pos) + 1) & mask;
580            for (;;) {
581                if ((curr = key[pos]) == null) {
582                    key[last] = null;
583                    value[last] = null;
584                    return;
585                }
586                slot = (hasher.hash(curr))
587                        & mask;
588                if (last <= pos ? last >= slot || slot > pos : last >= slot
589                        && slot > pos)
590                    break;
591                pos = (pos + 1) & mask;
592            }
593            key[last] = curr;
594            value[last] = value[pos];
595            fixOrder(pos, last);
596        }
597    }
598    public V remove(final Object k) {
599        if (k == null) {
600            if (containsNullKey)
601                return removeNullEntry();
602            return defRetValue;
603        }
604        K curr;
605        final K[] key = this.key;
606        int pos;
607        // The starting point.
608        if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) == null)
609            return defRetValue;
610        if (hasher.areEqual(k, curr))
611            return removeEntry(pos);
612        while (true) {
613            if ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null)
614                return defRetValue;
615            if (hasher.areEqual(k, curr))
616                return removeEntry(pos);
617        }
618    }
619    private V setValue(final int pos, final V v) {
620        final V oldValue = value[pos];
621        value[pos] = v;
622        return oldValue;
623    }
624    /**
625     * Removes the mapping associated with the first key in iteration order.
626     *
627     * @return the value previously associated with the first key in iteration
628     *         order.
629     * @throws NoSuchElementException
630     *             is this map is empty.
631     */
632    public V removeFirst() {
633        if (size == 0)
634            throw new NoSuchElementException();
635        final int pos = order.removeIndex(0);
636
637        size--;
638        final V v = value[pos];
639        if (pos == n) {
640            containsNullKey = false;
641            key[n] = null;
642            value[n] = null;
643        } else
644            shiftKeys(pos);
645        if (size < maxFill / 4 && n > DEFAULT_INITIAL_SIZE)
646            rehash(n / 2);
647        return v;
648    }
649    /**
650     * Removes the mapping associated with the last key in iteration order.
651     *
652     * @return the value previously associated with the last key in iteration
653     *         order.
654     * @throws NoSuchElementException
655     *             is this map is empty.
656     */
657    public V removeLast() {
658        if (size == 0)
659            throw new NoSuchElementException();
660        final int pos = order.items[order.size-1];
661        order.pop();
662        size--;
663        final V v = value[pos];
664        if (pos == n) {
665            containsNullKey = false;
666            key[n] = null;
667            value[n] = null;
668        } else
669            shiftKeys(pos);
670        if (size < maxFill / 4 && n > DEFAULT_INITIAL_SIZE)
671            rehash(n / 2);
672        return v;
673    }
674    private void moveIndexToFirst(final int i) {
675        if(size <= 1 || order.items[0] == i)
676            return;
677        order.moveToFirst(i);
678    }
679    private void moveIndexToLast(final int i) {
680        if(size <= 1 || order.items[order.size-1] == i)
681            return;
682        order.moveToLast(i);
683    }
684    /**
685     * Returns the value to which the given key is mapped; if the key is
686     * present, it is moved to the first position of the iteration order.
687     *
688     * @param k
689     *            the key.
690     * @return the corresponding value, or the
691     *         {@linkplain #defaultReturnValue() default return value} if no
692     *         value was present for the given key.
693     */
694    public V getAndMoveToFirst(final K k) {
695        if (k == null) {
696            if (containsNullKey) {
697                moveIndexToFirst(n);
698                return value[n];
699            }
700            return defRetValue;
701        }
702        K curr;
703        final K[] key = this.key;
704        int pos;
705        // The starting point.
706        if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) == null)
707            return defRetValue;
708        if (hasher.areEqual(k, curr)) {
709            moveIndexToFirst(pos);
710            return value[pos];
711        }
712        // There's always an unused entry.
713        while (true) {
714            if ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null)
715                return defRetValue;
716            if (hasher.areEqual(k, curr)) {
717                moveIndexToFirst(pos);
718                return value[pos];
719            }
720        }
721    }

737            return defRetValue;

743        if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) == null)
744            return defRetValue;

759    /**
760     * Adds a pair to the map; if the key is already present, it is moved to the
761     * first position of the iteration order.
762     *
763     * @param k
764     *            the key.
765     * @param v
766     *            the value.
767     * @return the old value, or the {@linkplain #defaultReturnValue() default
768     *         return value} if no value was present for the given key.
769     */
770    public V putAndMoveToFirst(final K k, final V v) {
771        int pos;
772        if (k == null) {
773            if (containsNullKey) {
774                moveIndexToFirst(n);
775                return setValue(n, v);
776            }
777            containsNullKey = true;
778            pos = n;
779        } else {
780            K curr;
781            final K[] key = this.key;
782            // The starting point.
783            if (!((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) == null)) {
784                if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k)) {
785                    moveIndexToFirst(pos);
786                    return setValue(pos, v);
787                }
788                while (!((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null))
789                    if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k)) {
790                        moveIndexToFirst(pos);
791                        return setValue(pos, v);
792                    }
793            }
794        }
795        key[pos] = k;
796        value[pos] = v;
797        order.insert(0, pos);
798        if (size++ >= maxFill)
799            rehash(arraySize(size, f));
800        return defRetValue;
801    }
802    /**
803     * Adds a pair to the map; if the key is already present, it is moved to the
804     * last position of the iteration order.
805     *
806     * @param k
807     *            the key.
808     * @param v
809     *            the value.
810     * @return the old value, or the {@linkplain #defaultReturnValue() default
811     *         return value} if no value was present for the given key.
812     */
813    public V putAndMoveToLast(final K k, final V v) {
814        int pos;
815        if (k == null) {
816            if (containsNullKey) {
817                moveIndexToLast(n);
818                return setValue(n, v);
819            }
820            containsNullKey = true;
821            pos = n;
822        } else {
823            K curr;
824            final K[] key = this.key;
825            // The starting point.
826            if (!((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) == null)) {
827                if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k)) {
828                    moveIndexToLast(pos);
829                    return setValue(pos, v);
830                }
831                while (!((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null))
832                    if (hasher.areEqual(curr, k)) {
833                        moveIndexToLast(pos);
834                        return setValue(pos, v);
835                    }
836            }
837        }
838        key[pos] = k;
839        value[pos] = v;
840        if(order.peek() != pos)
841            order.add(pos);
842        if (size++ >= maxFill)
843            rehash(arraySize(size, f));
844        return defRetValue;
845    }

856            return value[pos];

858        while (true) {
859            if ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null)
860                return defRetValue;

862                return value[pos];
863        }

925    /**
926     * Swaps the positions in the ordering for the given items, if they are both present. Returns true if the ordering
927     * changed as a result of this call, or false if it stayed the same (which can be because left or right was not
928     * present, or because left and right are the same reference (so swapping would do nothing)).
929     * @param left an item that should be present in this OrderedMap
930     * @param right an item that should be present in this OrderedMap
931     * @return true if this OrderedMap changed in ordering as a result of this call, or false otherwise
932     */
933    public boolean swap(final K left, final K right)
934    {
935        if(left == right) return false;
936        int l = indexOf(left);
937        if(l < 0) return false;
938        int r = indexOf(right);
939        if(r < 0) return false;
940        order.swap(l, r);
941        return true;
942    }
943    /**
944     * Swaps the given indices in the ordering, if they are both valid int indices. Returns true if the ordering
945     * changed as a result of this call, or false if it stayed the same (which can be because left or right referred to
946     * an out-of-bounds index, or because left and right are equal (so swapping would do nothing)).
947     * @param left an index of an item in this OrderedMap, at least 0 and less than {@link #size()}
948     * @param right an index of an item in this OrderedMap, at least 0 and less than {@link #size()}
949     * @return true if this OrderedMap changed in ordering as a result of this call, or false otherwise
950     */
951    public boolean swapIndices(final int left, final int right)
952    {
953        if(left < 0 || right < 0 || left >= order.size || right >= order.size || left == right) return false;
954        order.swap(left, right);
955        return true;
956    }

960        if (k == null)
961            return containsNullKey;
962        K curr;
963        final K[] key = this.key;
964        int pos;
965        // The starting point.
966        if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(k)) & mask]) == null)
967            return false;
968        if (hasher.areEqual(k, curr))
969            return true;
970        // There's always an unused entry.
971        while (true) {
972            if ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null)
973                return false;

975                return true;
976        }

978    public boolean containsValue(final Object v) {
979        final V[] value = this.value;
980        final K[] key = this.key;
981        if (containsNullKey
982                && (value[n] == null ? v == null : value[n].equals(v)))
983            return true;
984        for (int i = n; i-- != 0;)
985            if (key[i] != null
986                    && (value[i] == null ? v == null : value[i].equals(v)))
987                return true;
988        return false;

1079     * Modifies the ordering for a shift from s to d.
1080     * <br>
1081     * This method will complete in linear time unless the source position is first or last.
1082     *
1083     * @param s the source position.
1084     * @param d the destination position.
1085     */
1086    protected void fixOrder(int s, int d) {
1087        if(size == 0)
1088            return;
1089        if (size == 1 || order.items[0] == s) {
1090            order.set(0, d);
1091        }
1092        else if (order.items[order.size-1] == s) {
1093            order.set(order.size - 1, d);
1094        }
1095        else
1096        {
1097            order.set(order.indexOf(s), d);
1098        }

1133    /**
1134     * A list iterator over a OrderedMap.
1135     *
1136     * <P>
1137     * This class provides a list iterator over a OrderedMap. The
1138     * constructor runs in constant time.
1139     */
1140    private class MapIterator {
1141        /**
1142         * The entry that will be returned by the next call to
1143         * {@link java.util.ListIterator#previous()} (or <code>null</code> if no
1144         * previous entry exists).
1145         */
1146        int prev = -1;
1147        /**
1148         * The entry that will be returned by the next call to
1149         * {@link java.util.ListIterator#next()} (or <code>null</code> if no
1150         * next entry exists).
1151         */
1152        int next;
1153        /**
1154         * The last entry that was returned (or -1 if we did not iterate or used
1155         * {@link java.util.Iterator#remove()}).
1156         */
1157        int curr = -1;
1158        /**
1159         * The current index (in the sense of a {@link java.util.ListIterator}).
1160         * Note that this value is not meaningful when this iterator has been
1161         * created using the nonempty constructor.
1162         */
1163        int index;
1164        private MapIterator() {
1165            next = size == 0 ? -1 : order.items[0];
1166            index = 0;
1167        }
1168        public boolean hasNext() {
1169            return next != -1;
1170        }
1171        public boolean hasPrevious() {
1172            return prev != -1;
1173        }
1174        private void ensureIndexKnown() {
1175            if (index >= 0)
1176                return;
1177            if (prev == -1) {
1178                index = 0;
1179                return;
1180            }
1181            if (next == -1) {
1182                index = size;
1183                return;
1184            }
1185            index = 0;
1186        }
1187        public int nextIndex() {
1188            ensureIndexKnown();
1189            return index + 1;
1190        }
1191        public int previousIndex() {
1192            ensureIndexKnown();
1193            return index - 1;
1194        }
1195        public int nextEntry() {
1196            if (!hasNext())
1197                throw new NoSuchElementException();
1198            curr = next;
1199            if(++index >= order.size)
1200                next = -1;
1201            else
1202                next = order.get(index);//(int) link[curr];
1203            prev = curr;
1204            return curr;
1205        }
1206        public int previousEntry() {
1207            if (!hasPrevious())
1208                throw new NoSuchElementException();
1209            curr = prev;
1210            if(--index < 1)
1211                prev = -1;
1212            else
1213                prev = order.get(index - 1);
1214            next = curr;
1215            return curr;
1216        }
1217        public void remove() {
1218            ensureIndexKnown();
1219            if (curr == -1)
1220                throw new IllegalStateException();
1221            if (curr == prev) {
1222                /*
1223                 * If the last operation was a next(), we are removing an entry
1224                 * that precedes the current index, and thus we must decrement
1225                 * it.
1226                 */
1227                if(--index >= 1)
1228                    prev = order.get(index - 1); //(int) (link[curr] >>> 32);
1229                else
1230                    prev = -1;
1231            } else {
1232                if(index < order.size - 1)
1233                    next = order.get(index + 1);
1234                else
1235                    next = -1;
1236            }
1237            order.removeIndex(index);
1238            size--;
1239            int last, slot, pos = curr;
1240            curr = -1;
1241            if (pos == n) {
1242                containsNullKey = false;
1243                key[n] = null;
1244                value[n] = null;
1245            } else {
1246                K curr;
1247                final K[] key = OrderedMap.this.key;
1248                // We have to horribly duplicate the shiftKeys() code because we
1249                // need to update next/prev.
1250                for (;;) {
1251                    pos = ((last = pos) + 1) & mask;
1252                    for (;;) {
1253                        if ((curr = key[pos]) == null) {
1254                            key[last] = null;
1255                            value[last] = null;
1256                            return;
1257                        }
1258                        slot = (hasher.hash(curr)) & mask;
1259                        if (last <= pos
1260                                ? last >= slot || slot > pos
1261                                : last >= slot && slot > pos)
1262                            break;
1263                        pos = (pos + 1) & mask;
1264                    }
1265                    key[last] = curr;
1266                    value[last] = value[pos];
1267                    if (next == pos)
1268                        next = last;
1269                    if (prev == pos)
1270                        prev = last;
1271                    fixOrder(pos, last);
1272                }
1273            }
1274        }
1275        public int skip(final int n) {
1276            int i = n;
1277            while (i-- != 0 && hasNext())
1278                nextEntry();
1279            return n - i - 1;
1280        }
1281        public int back(final int n) {
1282            int i = n;
1283            while (i-- != 0 && hasPrevious())
1284                previousEntry();
1285            return n - i - 1;
1286        }
1287    }
1288    private class EntryIterator extends MapIterator
1289            implements
1290            Iterator<Entry<K, V>>, Serializable {
1291        private static final long serialVersionUID = 0L;
1292
1293        private MapEntry entry;
1294        public EntryIterator() {
1295        }
1296        public MapEntry next() {
1297            return entry = new MapEntry(nextEntry());

1921        final V[] newValue = (V[]) new Object[newN + 1];

2020    /**
2021     * Returns a hash code for this map.
2022     *
2023     * This method overrides the generic method provided by the superclass.
2024     * Since <code>equals()</code> is not overriden, it is important that the
2025     * value returned by this method is the same value as the one returned by
2026     * the overriden method.
2027     *
2028     * @return a hash code for this map.
2029     */
2030    public int hashCode() {
2031        int h = 0;
2032        for (int j = realSize(), i = 0, t = 0; j-- != 0;) {
2033            while (key[i] == null)
2034                i++;
2035            if (this != key[i])
2036                t = hasher.hash(key[i]);
2037            if (this != value[i])
2038                t ^= value[i] == null ? 0 : value[i].hashCode();
2039            h += t;
2040            i++;
2041        }
2042        // Zero / null keys have hash zero.
2043        if (containsNullKey)
2044            h += value[n] == null ? 0 : value[n].hashCode();
2045        return h;
2046    }

2375    /**
2376     * Swaps a key, original, for another key, replacement, while keeping replacement at the same point in the iteration
2377     * order as original and keeping it associated with the same value (which also keeps its iteration index).
2378     * Be aware that if both original and replacement are present in the OrderedMap, this will still replace original
2379     * with replacement but will also remove the other occurrence of replacement to avoid duplicate keys. This can throw
2380     * off the expected order because the duplicate could be at any point in the ordering when it is removed. You may
2381     * want to prefer {@link #alterCarefully(Object, Object)} if you don't feel like checking by hand for whether
2382     * replacement is already present, but using this method is perfectly reasonable if you know overlaps won't happen.
2383     * @param original the key to find and swap out
2384     * @param replacement the key to replace original with
2385     * @return the value associated with original before, and replacement now
2386     */
2387    public V alter(final K original, final K replacement) {
2388        V v;
2389        int idx;
2390        if (original == null) {
2391            if (containsNullKey) {
2392                v = value[n];
2393                idx = alterNullEntry();
2394                putAt(replacement, v, idx);
2395                return v;
2396            }
2397            else
2398                v = defRetValue;
2399            return v;
2400        }
2401        K curr;
2402        final K[] key = this.key;
2403        int pos;
2404        // The starting point.
2405        if ((curr = key[pos = (hasher.hash(original)) & mask]) == null)
2406            return defRetValue;
2407        if (hasher.areEqual(original, curr))
2408        {
2409            v = value[pos];
2410            idx = alterEntry(pos);
2411            putAt(replacement, v, idx);
2412            return v;
2413        }
2414        while (true) {
2415            if ((curr = key[pos = (pos + 1) & mask]) == null)
2416                return defRetValue;
2417            if (hasher.areEqual(original, curr))
2418            {
2419                v = value[pos];
2420                idx = alterEntry(pos);
2421                putAt(replacement, v, idx);
2422                return v;
2423            }
2424        }
2425    }

2543     * Given alternating key and value arguments in pairs, puts each key-value pair into this OrderedMap as if by
2544     * calling {@link #put(Object, Object)} repeatedly for each pair. This mimics the parameter syntax used for
2545     * {@link #makeMap(Object, Object, Object...)}, and can be used to retain that style of insertion after an
2546     * OrderedMap has been instantiated.
2547     * @param k0 the first key to add
2548     * @param v0 the first value to add
2549     * @param rest an array or vararg of keys and values in pairs; should contain alternating K, V, K, V... elements
2550     * @return this, after adding all viable key-value pairs given
2551     */
2552    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
2553    public OrderedMap<K, V> putPairs(K k0, V v0, Object... rest)
2554    {

2556        {
2557            put(k0, v0);
2558            return this;
2559        }
2560        put(k0, v0);
2561
2562        for (int i = 0; i < rest.length - 1; i+=2) {
2563            try {
2564                put((K) rest[i], (V) rest[i + 1]);
2565            }catch (ClassCastException ignored) {
2566            }
2567        }
2568        return this;

2571    /**
2572     * Makes an OrderedMap (OM) with the given load factor (which should be between 0.1 and 0.9), key and value types
2573     * inferred from the types of k0 and v0, and considers all remaining parameters key-value pairs, casting the Objects
2574     * at positions 0, 2, 4... etc. to K and the objects at positions 1, 3, 5... etc. to V. If rest has an odd-number
2575     * length, then it discards the last item. If any pair of items in rest cannot be cast to the correct type of K or
2576     * V, then this inserts nothing for that pair. This is similar to the makeOM method in the Maker class, but does not
2577     * allow setting the load factor (since that extra parameter can muddle how javac figures out which generic types
2578     * the map should use), nor does it log debug information if a cast fails. The result should be the same otherwise.
2579     * <br>
2580     * This is named makeMap to indicate that it expects key and value parameters, unlike a Set or List. This convention
2581     * may be extended to other data structures that also have static methods for instantiation.
2582     * @param k0 the first key; used to infer the types of other keys if generic parameters aren't specified.
2583     * @param v0 the first value; used to infer the types of other values if generic parameters aren't specified.
2584     * @param rest an array or vararg of keys and values in pairs; should contain alternating K, V, K, V... elements
2585     * @param <K> the type of keys in the returned OrderedMap; if not specified, will be inferred from k0
2586     * @param <V> the type of values in the returned OrderedMap; if not specified, will be inferred from v0
2587     * @return a freshly-made OrderedMap with K keys and V values, using k0, v0, and the contents of rest to fill it
2588     */
2589    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
2590    public static <K, V> OrderedMap<K, V> makeMap(K k0, V v0, Object... rest)
2591    {
2592        if(rest == null || rest.length == 0)
2593        {
2594            OrderedMap<K, V> om = new OrderedMap<>(2);
2595            om.put(k0, v0);
2596            return om;
2597        }
2598        OrderedMap<K, V> om = new OrderedMap<>(1 + (rest.length >> 1));
2599        om.put(k0, v0);
2600
2601        for (int i = 0; i < rest.length - 1; i+=2) {
2602            try {
2603                om.put((K) rest[i], (V) rest[i + 1]);
2604            }catch (ClassCastException ignored) {
2605            }
2606        }
2607        return om;
2608    }
